{{about|the American comedian|the Canadian politician|Brent Morin (politician)}} {{Infobox person | name = Brent Morin | image = Brent Morin slanted.jpg | image_size = 280px | caption = Morin in 2014 | alt = Brent Morin | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|08|31}} | birth_place = [[South Windsor, Connecticut|South Windsor]], [[Connecticut]] [[United States|U.S.]] | residence = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] [[United States|U.S.]] | occupation = {{Flatlist | *Comedian *actor *writer}} | years_active = 2011–present | education = [[Columbia College Hollywood|Columbia College]] | website = {{URL|brentmor.in}} }} '''Brent Morin''' (born August 31, 1986)<ref>{{cite tweet|number=648611398180818944|user=ksdknews|title=august 31st 1986. Send me an expensive gift|accessdate=19 March 2016|date=28 September 2015}}</ref> is a Los Angeles-based American comedian, stand-up comic, actor and writer.<ref name=FoxLA-S3-Special-2015>{{cite news|last1=DeSocio|first1=Jeffrey Thomas|title=Brent Morin on 'Undateable' and new comedy special|url=http://www.foxla.com/good-day/good-day-la-celebrity-interviews/55030402-story|accessdate=1 December 2015|work=[[KTTV]]|date=1 December 2015}}</ref> He was a panelist in the sixth season of ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'' and played Justin Kearney on the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Undateable]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/undateable/video/bridgit-mendler-sings-undateable/2851815|title="Undateable"- Bridgit Mendler and the Undateable Cast|work=[[NBC]]|date=8 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312081804/http://www.nbc.com/undateable/video/bridgit-mendler-sings-undateable/2851815|archivedate=12 March 2015|df=}}</ref> and the agent Hobbs on the sci-fi web-series ''Crunch Time'', on [[Rooster Teeth]].<ref name=nerdist/> In 2015, Morin released his [[stand-up comedy]] show, ''I'm Brent Morin'', exclusively on [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/12/brent-morin-im-brent-morin-review.html|title=Brent Morin: I’m Brent Morin Review|work=Paste Magazine|date=8 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref>
== Early life == Morin was born in [[South Windsor, Connecticut|South Windsor]], [[Connecticut]], to two inner city high school English teacher parents.<ref name=SerialOptimist-Super-2013>{{cite web|last1=Hill|first1=Jazmine|title=Interview With The Super Hilarious & Super Favorite Brent Morin|url=http://www.serialoptimist.com/interviews/interview-with-the-super-hilarious-super-favorite-brent-morin-19480.html|website=Serial Optimist|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=12 July 2013}}</ref> Morin has an older brother, who was a concert pianist, and a younger brother, who became a professional figure skater. He graduated from [[South Windsor High School]].<ref name=SerialOptimist-Super-2013 /> He is of Irish and Italian background.<ref name=WGN-Bill&Wendy-2014>{{cite web|last1=Leff|first1=Bill|last2=Snyder|first2=Wendy|title=Brent Morin|url=http://wgnradio.com/2014/03/08/brent-morin/|website=[[WGN Radio]]|publisher=[[Tribune Broadcasting]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=8 March 2014}}</ref>
== Career == [[File:Brent Morin, Bill Lawrence, Bridgit Mendler, Rick Glassman from NBC Undateable.jpg|left|thumb|220px|Morin (left) with the cast of ''[[Undateable]]'', in 2015.]] Morin moved to Los Angeles at 18 to study at a film school at [[Columbia College Hollywood]].<ref name=BostonGlobe-Shows-2014>{{cite news|last1=Juul|first1=Matt|title=Comedian Brent Morin Talks ‘Undateable,’ Boston Shows|url=http://www.boston.com/entertainment/celebrity/2014/06/04/comedian-brent-morin-talks-undateable-boston-shows/0T5bBWtBbgzOxHJcmOLVYK/story.html|accessdate=18 July 2014|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=4 June 2014}}</ref> Although he graduated with a film degree, Morin started doing stand-up and eventually decided that was what he wanted to do.<ref name=SerialOptimist-Super-2013 /> Morin has said that he was inspired by his idols, [[Albert Brooks]] and [[Woody Allen]].<ref name=BostonGlobe-Shows-2014 /> After graduation, he worked as a production assistant with [[Conan O'Brien]] on ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien]]'' on [[NBC]] and continued with ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'' on [[TBS (U.S. TV channel)|TBS]].<ref name=SerialOptimist-Super-2013 /><ref name=Variety-P.A.-2013>{{cite web|last1=Blair|first1=Iain|title=Standup Brent Morin Climbs from Conan P.A. to Center Stage|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/features/standup-brent-morin-climbs-from-conan-p-a-to-center-stage-1200564534/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=17 July 2013}}</ref> He went from being a general office production assistant to becoming the set production assistant/[[Andy Richter]]’s [[stand-in]].<ref name=AccessHwood-LongtimePal-2014>{{cite web|last1=Lash|first1=Jolie|title='Undateable' Q&A: Brent Morin On Teaming Up With Longtime Pal Chris D'Elia For Laughs|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/undateable-qanda-brent-morin-on-teaming-up-with-longtime-pal-chris-delia-for-laughs_article_94810|website=[[Access Hollywood]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=29 May 2014}}</ref> Morin has appeared regularly as a stand-up comic on shows with ''[[The Comedy Store]]'', ''[[The Improv]]'' and ''[[Laugh Factory]]'',<ref name=LaughFactory-Bio>{{cite web|title=Brent Morin Biography|url=http://www.laughfactory.com/BrentMorin|website=[[Laugh Factory]]|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> as well as on tours throughout the United States.<ref name=USAToday-SocialMedia-2014>{{cite news|last1=Graham|first1=Jefferson|title=D'Elia and Morin sing for their social media supper |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/talkingtech/2014/06/10/delia-and-morin-sing-for-their-social-media-supper/10250665/|accessdate=18 July 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|date=10 June 2014}}</ref> In his network TV debut, Morin co-starred in the [[Bill Lawrence (TV producer)|Bill Lawrence]] NBC series ''[[Undateable]],''<ref name=NYTimes-UndateableReview-2014>{{cite news|last1=Stanley|first1=Alessandra|title=A Bunch of Friends? Yeah, Again: ‘Undateable’ Keeps a Sitcom Formula Alive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/29/arts/television/undateable-keeps-a-sitcom-formula-alive.html?_r=0|accessdate=18 July 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> a multi-camera sitcom with a live audience, which was based on the book ''Undateable: 311 Things Guys Do That Guarantee They Won't Be Dating or Having Sex'' by Ellen Rakieten and Anne Coyle.<ref name=HReporter-UndateableCastLead-2013>{{cite web |last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=NBC's Bill Lawrence Comedy 'Undateable' Casts Lead |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/nbcs-bill-lawrence-comedy-undateable-422689|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=20 February 2013}}</ref>
Morin portrayed Justin Kearney, the owner of Black Eyes Bar and hopeless romantic roommate of Danny (played by ''[[Chris D'Elia]]''). ''[[Undateable]]'' was unique in that it was a cast full of stand-up comedians who were good friends before the show aired. The show often incorporates improv, with Morin playing Felix to D'Elia's grouch Oscar à la ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]].''<ref name=WE-5ReasonstoWatch-2014>{{cite web|last1=Ray|first1=Lincee|title=5 reasons to watch ‘Undateable’|url=http://community.ew.com/2014/06/19/five-reasons-to-watch-undateable/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=19 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=Collider-Talks-2014>{{cite web|last1=Radish|first1=Christina|title=Brent Morin Talks 'Undateable,' Performing Stand-Up, His Weird Life Journey with Chris D’Elia, Being Funny on Camera, Singing on the Show, and More|url=http://collider.com/brent-morin-undateable-interview/|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=6 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=LarryKing-Cast-2014>{{cite web|last1=King|first1=Larry|title=The Cast of "Undateable"|url=http://www.ora.tv/larrykingnow/the-cast-of-undateable-0_3yambvfisshv|website=Larry King Now|accessdate=26 July 2014|date=11 June 2014}}</ref> Lawrence and the cast ([[Chris D'Elia]], Morin, [[Ron Funches]], and Rick Glassman) went on a series of stand-up tour dates, with an appearance on [[@midnight]] to promote the show.<ref name=Variety-HitRoad-2014>{{cite web|last1=Littleton|first1=Cynthia|title=Bill Lawrence and ‘Undateable’ Stars Hit the Road to Promote NBC Comedy ‘Undateable’|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/bill-lawrence-and-undateable-stars-hit-the-road-to-promote-nbc-comedy-undateable-1201120161/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=25 February 2014}}</ref><ref name=Grantland-LawrenceTourDiary-2014>{{cite web|last1=Lawrence|first1=Bill|title=The ‘Undateable’ Comedy Tour: How to Launch (or Not Launch) a TV Show in 2014|url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/the-undateable-comedy-tour-how-to-launch-or-not-launch-a-tv-show-in-2014/|website=[[Grantland]]|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> In 2016, Morin was cast for the [[Rooster Teeth]] web series, ''Crunch Time''.
==Personal life== Morin dated actress Angie Simms for two years, confirming their relationship in 2016,<ref>https://www.twitter.com/brentmorin/status/777122384197275648?lang=en</ref><ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/-98syIPxio/</ref> and breakup in 2017.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TO2_IpHmcA4</ref>
